 -->The '''scientific method''' is a body of [[Scientific technique|techniques]] for investigating [[Phenomenon|phenomena]], acquiring new [[knowledge]], or correcting and integrating previous knowledge.<ref name="Goldhaber 2010 page=940">{{harvnb|Goldhaber|Nieto|2010|page=940}}</ref> To be termed scientific, a method of [[inquiry]] is commonly based on [[empirical]] or [[Measurement|measurable]] evidence subject to specific principles of reasoning.<ref>"[4] Rules for the study of [[natural philosophy]]", {{harvnb|Newton transl|1999|pp=794–6}}, after Book '''3''', ''The System of the World''.</ref> The [[OxfordDictionaries.com|Oxford Dictionaries Online]] define the scientific method as "a method or procedure that has characterized [[natural science]] since the 17th century, consisting in systematic observation, measurement, and [[experiment]], and the formulation, testing, and modification of [[Hypothesis|hypotheses]]".<ref>{{Citation | date = 2016 | title = Oxford Dictionaries: British and World English | chapter = scientific method | url = http://www.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/english/scientific-method | accessdate = 28 May 2016 }}</ref>

The scientific method is an ongoing process, which usually begins with observations about the natural world. Human beings are naturally inquisitive, so they often come up with questions about things they see or hear and often develop ideas (hypotheses) about why things are the way they are. The best hypotheses lead to predictions that can be tested in various ways, including making further observations about nature. In general, the strongest tests of hypotheses come from carefully controlled and replicated experiments that gather empirical data. Depending on how well the tests match the predictions, the original hypothesis may require refinement, alteration, expansion or even rejection. If a particular hypothesis becomes very well supported a general [[scientific theory|theory]] may be developed.<ref name="Garland2015">{{cite web
